metadata.name: 0RAL B1NARY: “BINARY ODE” #288
metadata.description:
An “algorhythmic” exploration of the oral/aural tradition in poetry. 

“Zero is a time of night.
Zero is the color of snow.
Zero is the space between notes.
Zero is the silence between words.
Zero is the pause before breath.
Zero is void in the heart of a crowd.
Zero is not nothing, but it’s not everything.
One is a time of day.
One is the color of spring grass in sunlight.
One is the warmth at the back of my neck when I turn to find you standing there.
One is the rhythm at the base of my spine.
One is the peace at the core of my being.
One is the sound of your voice in the dark.
And one more thing:
Without one I am nothing…”
–Technelegy 
 

Fusing AI-powered verse, spoken word, original music and visuals all in generative composition, this playful ode to our universal language is inspired by Stiles’ binary-based art and Stern’s performative poetics. The experiment centers on a transhuman poem by Stiles’ AI alter ego, Technelegy, voiced as zeroes and ones, layered with human- and machine-generated sound – evoking ancient data transmissions in the oral tradition as well as the immersive potential of multisensorial, multimedia, metaversal language and literature. Brought into existence via the blockchain, it is a new form of “token word poetry.”


As with the duo’s other poetry “unreadings,” all minters will receive an airdropped broadside of the full poem after all editions are collected. A 1/1 media-rich version of the entire poem will also be made available. 
 
Poetic traits:
- 321 editions performed by the algorithm, out of billions of possible combinations
- Each unique piece contains between 3 and 6 (out of 60) lines of generative text from a poem by Technelegy – a custom text generator fine-tuned on Stiles’ writing and research material, seeded with prompts from Stiles’ and Stern’s work – translated into binary and performed by Stiles
- 24 possible binary backbeats performed by Stern in his “Nathaniel Fun Time” (NFT) stylings, and generatively re-mixed
- 98 possible intros
- 15 musical stems composed by Kris Bones, generating millions of possible mixes
- Thousands of possible ending combinations 
- 5 fonts, layered in billions of potential ways, including Stern and Stiles’ custom AI font, NNFT (Neural Network Font Type), developed for their ongoing collaboration, “Mother Computer”
- 13 color palettes based on Stern and Stiles’ respective artworka
- Very rare attributes including music-less performance, poem-less music, repeated “B1nary 0de” (title only)

Click to start and stop or replay. Although the first play through will be the same every time, starting and stopping may create minor variations in your mix (though not any of the core attributes).

0RAL B1NARY: “BINARY ODE” was produced with partial support from Refraction DAO’s Creative Grants program, and premiered as part of Refraction Festival at Art Basel Miami 2022. 15% of primary sales go to Refraction, and 5% of primary sales will be donated to Black Girls Code.

metadata.name: Magnolia Portrait #69
metadata.description:
Inspired by observation of the incessantly-rooted Pteridophyte and Magnolia, the cognominal series, “Magnolia”, portrays a manifestation of layers of constant streams crossing dynamically in a flow. Through years of growing in fluxed vapor, its knots and roots construct organized and rhythmic patterns within chaotic orders. From two-dimensional layouts to three-dimensional composition, “Magnolia” absorbs its fundamental image, and extend it even further — creating the core of generative artwork.

Press "s" to download

metadata.name: Zephyr #30
metadata.description:
The name Zephyr traces back to Zephyrus, the Greek god of the west wind, and refers to any light breeze. The flowing particles get pushed around by a zephyr, creating interesting and organic patterns.

Live Mode Controls:

- Default is 2000x2000 pixel canvas. Press “1” for 1000x1000px canvas, “3” for 3000x3000px, “4” for 4000x4000px
- Press 'p' to save a png of the canvas.

Created using p5.js

Licensed under CC BY-NC 4.0

metadata.name: Waves and Ripples #67
metadata.description:
Waves and Ripples is an implementation of a continuous CA, where wave like behaviours are obtained from the influence of neighbour cells over the cell itself. Depeding on the connections config for each cell, different patterns will emerge, creating waves, ripples, or a mix of both. When single loop is on, the calculations and drawings are done at once, which makes for a more chaotic visual.
Best enjoyed in full-screen :) 

Click anywhere to restart

Features : 
  shrinkFactor : 3 types
  connectArray: 16 possibilities,
  extraConnection: 4 types,
  mutualNeighbour: 40% chance,
  singleLoop: 30% chance
  monoChromo:  15% chance

Inspired by Matt Pearson's book.

metadata.name: RushGushBlush #30
metadata.description:
Let's celebrate #fxhashturnsone with a cascade of colors!

This is just my second release on fxhash and I couldn't be happier to dedicate this project, however simple, to this amazing community.

I could go on describing the details of this piece but honestly I just wanted to create something very colorful for the party, without putting too many hidden meanings! :)
(Or maybe not...)

Happy birthday fxhash!

---

80% of primary sales will be donated to the Processing Foundation and Save Pakistan.

---

There are 17 different palettes and 3 formats, hope you'll find a combination that makes you happy!
The texture might look weird in thumbnails, so I recommend opening the piece in full screen and/or download the png by pressing "s".

---

By Todemashi 2022
NFT License 2.0

### NOTES
Made with p5js.
This project uses fx(stdio) by @alt_escapism - https://altesc.art/stdio

metadata.name: BWEEPS  #78
metadata.description:
A minimalist, black-and-white generative profile picture (PFP) created to commemorate one-year anniversary of Bwople project by Gengoya. The artwork is derived from an initial sketch of Bwople which, despite being not the one that was chosen, still managed to captivate interests. The project provides a unique glimpse into an alternate universe in which Bwople could have been represented.

All images are hand-drawn work by Gengoya and composed by Vector Recite using PureSpider's fxhash-pfp maker tool.

To download the full size image on fx(hash):
- Click "open" below the image
- Left click on the image, a "Download image" button will appear on the bottom right.
- Click the "Download image" button.

metadata.name: broken laser printer #8
metadata.description:
If I have a super-power, it is this. When I get to within one meter of a printer or photocopier, they malfunction. Sometimes they jam, sometimes the sheets of paper get crumpled and torn, and other times the toner cartridges and drums get fouled and streaked.

This artwork is an abstract depiction of the state of printouts under the influence of my superpower. I always try to use my powers for good, but I am only human, and the result often has unintended side-effects.

Press "s" to save image.

Press "q" if you want to relieve stress caused by malfunctioning printers (does not affect the artwork in any way).

metadata.name: The City #310
metadata.description:
// The City //

Cities are the most complex human-made interventions on Earth. The human settlements are growing like huge organisms – and the growth is often impossible to plan, control or limit.
Cities as a phenomenon are with their incredible complexity highly enigmatic structures, that are as fascinating as they are terrifying.

This project is a study of the beauty of complexity.

Each city iteration is an entirely unique structure with unique hatching, arrangement of buildings, heights, sizes, additions and rare items.
The cities are made even more organic by the meticulous modelling of analog ink drawing.

The project is 100% generative. All lines, hatching and dots are generated for each iteration.

As a gesture of appreciation towards our supporters, 20% of royalties will go to the original minter.

Key commands:
Press 's' to save a png version
Press '2' to render at twice the resolution
Press 'b' to remove the colored background before saving

The loading progress is animated, hence the epileptic trigger warning.
Due to memory constraints on mobile devices, rendering uses a lower resolution on these.
-----------

Original concept by @Lax_raven
All code by @r1b2art

metadata.name: Sabler : Serengeti #174
metadata.description:
'Sabler : Serengeti' is a special edition reissue of the original Sabler generator in a vibrant 'Serengeti' palette which was omitted from the original collection. 

Towards the end of the production of the original Sabler collection, the creative decision was made to reduce the number of palettes from the thirteen that had been created to a smaller number, in order to improve the cohesiveness of the collection overall. While 'Serengeti' remained one of the stronger palettes, it was ultimately excluded in favour of the 'Annaliese' palette, in homage to an Anni Albers tapestry that originally inspired the 'Sabler' collection. 

Here, the 'Serengeti' palette is provided as a companion piece to the original Sabler collection to give collectors the opportunity to pair their output with their existing collection if they choose.

Below follows an edited description for the original 'Sabler' collection:

'Sabler', an anagram of 'Albers', is a generative homage to the work of the Bauhaus textile artist Anni Albers.

The aesthetic of this piece and its proportions are guided by the Golden Ratio (1.618 : 1) and as such, each part of the composition relates in some way to its larger self.

As lines playfully extend and overlap one another from various grid segments, patterns appear, 'ghost' shadings emerge and complexity is implied even with the use of very simple elements.

There are no rarities or special features, other than for you to enjoy the unique qualities of your piece!

You can save a high resolution 3000px x 3000px PNG of your edition by pressing the 'S' key.

metadata.name: Ceremony #131
metadata.description:
This series celebrates fxhash turning one. #fxhashturnsone

I’m so grateful for this place and have ho idea how to adequately articulate how much this platform has changed my life, but it has. A million thanks to the team. You are so appreciated as are the artists and collectors that have made this such a beautiful community. 🥂

Definitely check out “Forever” mode by tapping “F” or mouse click/tap — it will animate (you guessed it) forever and will change its layout every 365 frames, in honor of this wonderful year, and every year after. Some forever modes will “never forget” and others will fade as they progress. No idea if that’s a metaphor but it is a trait, that much I know.

All primary sales are donated to Code/Art, which is a charity that uses “…Art to Inspire Girls in Computer Science.” Read about Code/Art here: https://www.code-art.com/

Ceremony uses public domain art (which is the original, more implicit version CC0) made exclusively by women.

See fxtext article linked from the project page for a gallery of the source material and other notes.

Ceremony is also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

F : “Forever” mode (tap after initial render completes)
P : Pause/Play
(mouse click/tap also works to start “Forever” mode or Pause/Play)

A : Add Grain (only works when paused in “Forever” mode.)
G : Toggle Grain (resets the whole piece)
M : Toggle Matte (resets the whole piece)

S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density (resets the whole piece)
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

If you want to start in "Forever" mode, you can append "&forever=true" to the url in the live view.
You can also add pixel density to the url by appending “&density=2” (or 3, 4, etc) to have it render at higher resolutions by default.

metadata.name: Primordial #124
metadata.description:
Primordial is a study of abstract forms. The algorithm, written in p5.js and WebGL, utilizes domain warping to create twisted fields of color and then overlays thousands of tiny lines to provide depth and texture. The outputs are chaotic but not completely formless, like a swirling mass of plasma from the early universe, or a strange proto-life form suspended in prehistoric ooze.

CONTROLS:

1-9: Increase resolution and save image in PNG format

B: Toggle borders on/off

F: Fullscreen
P: Portrait
L: Landscape
S: Square

For third party license information, please see license.md

David Brice Allen
October 2022

metadata.name: Verdant Brut #207
metadata.description:
Verdant translates to “lush, green” and Brut means “dry, raw, or unrefined.”

This series is less about impressions of nature, or vegetal growth… but rather the vibrant, lush world that abstract art can provide and while certain iterations may serve Brutalist aesthetics, it tries to focus on the unrefined/raw aspect of the definition with more fluid shapes that feel irregular and organic in a playful, almost adolescent way.

Palettes inspired by MOMO, Melissa Wiederrecht, Erik Swahn, Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, Paul Klee, Mareva Millarc, Ernst Mether-Borgström, Douglas Herbert Courtenay Auburn, Jim Harris, Alayne Spafford, Man Ray, Lajos Kassak and William Lachance. While the palettes may not always reflect their trademark colors (if they even have any) they are an homage to individual pieces by the respective artists that have influenced this series in their own way.

4878 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries.

For more info on the chosen palettes and other inspirations, see article linked from the main project page: Regarding Verdant Brut

In live mode:
‘S’ : save as png (2376 × 3360)
’V’ : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‘g=n’ : no grain
‘g=p’ : paper grain
‘h=t’ : high resolution mode, 5940 × 8400 (Chrome only)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append “&g=p&h=t” to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save the png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: Artifice #30
metadata.description:
This series is is about playful obfuscation.

The fxtext article linked on the main profect goes more in-depth into what is meant by that, as well as the events that led to this collection.

5640 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries. Palettes make up a third of the code.

In live mode:
‘S’ : save as png (3000 × 3600)
’V’ : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‘g=n’ : no grain
‘g=p’ : paper grain
‘h=t’ : high resolution mode, 9000 ×10600 (Chrome only, and may take a moment)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append “&g=p&h=t” to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save a png with those settings applied.
